content.description: Climb the pocketed arete/face at the bottom of the left wall. Guide calls this 5.9 but it is very stiff for that. Not a good warm up.
content.location: Third route on the left wall as you enter the Temple.

content.description: This is one of the worst routes we've done at Ten Sleep.  Chossy rock, contrived climbing, and uncharacteristically run out bolts.  Nothing on the Tu-Pac wall is worth hiking down here for.  Charlie has bolted some brilliant lines in the canyon, unfortunately this is not one of them.
content.location: The right most route on Tu-Pac Buttress.  The guide book list one more route to the right, "Rollin' with the safety off", but we couldn't find it.

content.description: The First route on the left when looking down into the temple. A sustained route from the ground up. Sorry, Charlie offers a variety of crimps and pockets that are somewhat difficult to spot. After the last bolt the holds disappear except for some crimps to make a final crux stab for the small ledge above the anchor.
content.location: First route on the left directly behind Dionysus.

content.description:
This route was the only thing that slightly redeemed this entire wall.  A big huck gets your blood flowing between the second and third bolts and three mini-cruxes will greet you higher up on the wall.  The pockets and still sharp so tread lightly.

The route however should have stopped about 15 feet lower and avoided the rotten (pegmatite?)rock that can be found up higher
content.location: Second route from the far right of the wall.

content.description: Good climbing up the white face to the CCB anchors.
Easy start then climbÂ up and left on tricky and continuous face climbing to bolted anchors.
content.location: Second route on the left as you enter the Temple.

content.description: Tough face climbing that joins CCB for the last three bolts.
Head toward the left-leaning rail and continue on good crimps and sidepulls to an airy mantle before reaching the shared anchor.
content.location: This route starts on a flat rock about 10-15 feet left of the boulder at the entrance to the Temple.  Look for the obvious rail.

content.description: Climbs the center of the immense roof through the obvious corner weakness.  One of the most aesthetic .12- in wyoming.
content.location: The roof.  You can't miss it.

content.description: Definitely one of the best 10's in tensleep, get over your intimidation and do it!!
content.protection: Spaciously bolted.  One locker through two chains at the top.
content.location: Once you find the Temple, you'll see the Char Char going up the amazing crack in the Main Cave.

content.description: A tricky start (which you can avoid by back-stemming) leads to thin holds that get bigger toward the end.  A bit thin for a warm-up.
content.location: Starts just below boulder at entrance to The Temple.

content.description: Climb the arete to the right of Black Forest. Shares the anchors with Black Forest. Given a 5.8 rating in the Anderson guidebook but seemed much stiffer than that.
content.location: Black Arete on the right as one is entering the main Temple area

content.description: This route is a brilliant line up bullet limestone that doesn't see many ascents as indicated by the lack of chalk as compared to other climbs in the area.  There are three distinct cruxes on this route.  The first comes leaving the flake & pulling around the bulge to the left, the second is gaining the head wall, the third is right below the anchors.  This route felt substantially harder than the 12b rating and harder than many of the other 12b climbs at Ten Sleep.
content.location: Starts at the base of a giant left facing flake about 30 ft up the hill and to climbers left of Char Char.
